    <h2 id="why-electrolyte-gummies">Why Electrolyte Gummies Matter More Than You Think</h2>

    <p>Your body loses 500-1,500mg of sodium per liter of sweat, along with significant amounts of potassium, magnesium, calcium, and chloride. For a moderate one-hour workout in warm conditions, total sweat losses range from 0.5 to 2.0 liters — meaning you can lose 250-3,000mg of sodium in a single training session. Water alone does not replace these minerals. Without adequate electrolyte replenishment, performance declines, cramps strike, and recovery slows.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">75%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of Americans are chronically dehydrated according to research published in the <em>Journal of Clinical Nutrition</em>. Even mild dehydration (1-2% body weight loss) impairs cognitive function, endurance, and strength output. <strong>Electrolytes are not optional for active people — they are essential.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <p>Electrolyte gummies solve the compliance problem that powders and drinks create. No shaker bottle. No measuring scoops. No flavor fatigue from drinking the same sports drink every day. Toss a few gummies in your gym bag, your carry-on, or your desk drawer, and you have immediate access to the minerals your body needs. The best electrolyte gummies deliver clinically relevant doses of sodium (200-500mg), potassium (100-200mg), and magnesium (30-60mg) per serving.</p>

    <p>If you are looking for performance supplements beyond hydration, our guides to the <a href="/sports/pre-workout-gummies/">best pre-workout gummies</a> and <a href="/best-creatine-gummies/">best creatine gummies</a> cover energy and strength support. For now, let us focus on the five electrolytes that keep your body running.</p>

    <!-- KEY ELECTROLYTES INFO-CARDS -->
    <h3>The 5 Essential Electrolytes Your Body Loses in Sweat</h3>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Sodium (Na+)</strong>
        <p>The primary electrolyte lost in sweat (500-1,500mg/L). Drives fluid absorption in the small intestine, maintains blood volume, and regulates nerve impulses. Low sodium causes hyponatremia: headaches, confusion, and in severe cases, seizures.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Potassium (K+)</strong>
        <p>Critical for muscle contraction and heart rhythm. Sweat losses average 150-300mg/L. Low potassium triggers muscle cramps, weakness, and irregular heartbeat. Most Americans consume only 50% of the daily adequate intake (2,600-3,400mg).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Magnesium (Mg2+)</strong>
        <p>Involved in over 300 enzymatic reactions including ATP production, protein synthesis, and muscle relaxation. Sweat losses are smaller (5-25mg/L) but cumulative. Low magnesium contributes to cramps, fatigue, and impaired recovery.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Calcium (Ca2+)</strong>
        <p>Essential for bone health, muscle contraction, and blood clotting. Sweat losses average 20-60mg/L. Athletes with high training volumes face increased calcium turnover. Chronic low calcium impairs bone density and increases fracture risk.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Chloride (Cl-)</strong>
        <p>Works alongside sodium to maintain fluid balance, blood pressure, and gastric acid production. Lost in sweat at rates similar to sodium. Most electrolyte supplements include chloride as sodium chloride (table salt) or potassium chloride.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>The American College of Sports Medicine recommends consuming <strong>300-600mg of sodium per hour</strong> during prolonged exercise (over 60 minutes) to maintain hydration status and prevent hyponatremia. A 2024 systematic review in <em>Sports Medicine</em> confirmed that electrolyte supplementation during exercise improves endurance performance by 1.7% on average compared to water alone.</p>
      <cite>American College of Sports Medicine Position Stand; Sports Medicine, 2024 — Systematic Review</cite>
    </div>

