      <ol>
        <li><strong>Purchased independently.</strong> Every product was purchased at full retail price through Amazon or the brand's direct website. No product was provided free, and no brand was informed of this evaluation.</li>
        <li><strong>Verified electrolyte doses.</strong> We cross-referenced supplement facts panels to confirm sodium, potassium, magnesium, and calcium content against label claims. Products with proprietary blends were flagged and penalized in scoring.</li>
        <li><strong>Tested in real conditions.</strong> A registered dietitian and three certified athletic trainers tested each product during gym sessions, outdoor runs (75-90 degrees F), long-distance cycling, and hiking over a 6-week period.</li>
        <li><strong>Measured hydration markers.</strong> Testers tracked urine color, body weight changes pre/post exercise, perceived thirst, muscle cramp occurrence, and subjective energy levels using a standardized 1-10 scale.</li>
        <li><strong>Evaluated taste and texture.</strong> All 28 products underwent blind taste testing. Testers rated flavor accuracy, sweetness balance, gummy texture, and aftertaste on a standardized scale.</li>
        <li><strong>Calculated long-term value.</strong> Cost per serving was computed using retail price at the time of testing. We also calculated cost per milligram of sodium to provide a normalized value comparison across products with different serving sizes.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <!-- WHEN YOU NEED ELECTROLYTE GUMMIES -->
    <h2 id="when-you-need">When You Need Electrolyte Gummies (5 Key Situations)</h2>

    <p>Electrolyte gummies are not just for athletes. Multiple common situations create electrolyte deficits that water alone cannot resolve. Understanding when your body loses electrolytes helps you supplement strategically rather than guessing.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Exercise (60+ Minutes)</strong>
        <p>Sweat rate during moderate exercise ranges from 0.5-2.0 L/hour. Each liter contains 500-1,500mg sodium, 150-300mg potassium, and smaller amounts of magnesium and calcium. Any session over 60 minutes demands electrolyte replacement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Hot Weather &amp; Humidity</strong>
        <p>Heat increases sweat rate by 30-50% compared to temperate conditions. Outdoor workers, hikers, and anyone in temperatures above 80 degrees F should supplement electrolytes proactively, not reactively after symptoms appear.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Air Travel</strong>
        <p>Airplane cabin humidity averages 10-20% — drier than most deserts. A 5-hour flight can produce 1.5-2 liters of insensible water loss through respiration and skin evaporation. Pack electrolyte gummies for flights over 3 hours.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Illness (Vomiting/Diarrhea)</strong>
        <p>Gastrointestinal illness causes rapid electrolyte depletion. The WHO's Oral Rehydration Solution protocol — the basis for Pedialyte's formula — was designed specifically for this scenario. Electrolyte gummies provide a convenient alternative to liquid ORS during recovery.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Ketogenic &amp; Low-Carb Diets</strong>
        <p>Reduced insulin on keto signals kidneys to excrete sodium, potassium, and magnesium at 2-3x normal rates. "Keto flu" symptoms — headaches, fatigue, cramps, brain fog — are almost always electrolyte deficiency. Supplementation resolves them within 24-48 hours.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Medical caution:</strong> If you take blood pressure medications, diuretics, or have kidney disease, consult your physician before supplementing electrolytes. Potassium supplementation can interact with ACE inhibitors and potassium-sparing diuretics, potentially causing dangerous hyperkalemia. Sodium supplementation may counteract the effects of antihypertensive medications.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- VS STRIP: GUMMIES vs POWDER vs DRINKS -->
    <h2 id="gummies-vs-powder-vs-drinks">Electrolyte Gummies vs. Powder vs. Drinks</h2>

    <p>Each electrolyte delivery format has distinct advantages. The right choice depends on your use case, lifestyle, and how much sodium you need per serving.</p>

    <div class="vs-strip">
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Electrolyte Gummies</strong>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Daily supplementation, travel, gym bags, offices, and on-the-go hydration.<br /><strong>Sodium per serving:</strong> 150-350mg.<br /><strong>Pros:</strong> No water or mixing required. Portable. Precise dosing. No flavor fatigue from daily drinking. Taste great.<br /><strong>Cons:</strong> Requires separate water intake. Lower max sodium doses than powder. Some contain added sugar.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Electrolyte Powder</strong>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Heavy sweaters, intense training, keto adaptation, and maximum electrolyte delivery.<br /><strong>Sodium per serving:</strong> 500-1,500mg.<br /><strong>Pros:</strong> Highest electrolyte doses available. Simultaneous hydration (mixed with water). Customizable concentration.<br /><strong>Cons:</strong> Requires water bottle and mixing. Flavor fatigue from daily drinking. Inconvenient for travel and gyms.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Sports Drinks (Gatorade, etc.)</strong>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> During exercise lasting 60+ minutes when you need electrolytes, carbs, and water simultaneously.<br /><strong>Sodium per serving:</strong> 160-270mg per 12oz.<br /><strong>Pros:</strong> All-in-one hydration, electrolytes, and energy. Widely available. No prep required.<br /><strong>Cons:</strong> High sugar content (21-34g per bottle). Heavy to carry. Limited to predetermined concentrations. Expensive per serving.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>Most athletes benefit from using multiple formats strategically: <strong>gummies for daily baseline hydration</strong>, powder mixed into a water bottle during training, and sports drinks during competitions or events lasting over 90 minutes. The best electrolyte strategy is the one you will actually follow consistently. If powder mixing feels like a chore and you skip it three days a week, gummies that you take every day will deliver better long-term results.</p>

    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Electrolyte Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do electrolyte gummies actually work for hydration?</summary>
      <p>Yes, electrolyte gummies deliver sodium, potassium, magnesium, and other minerals that facilitate water absorption and fluid balance. The key is dose: effective hydration requires at least 200-500mg sodium and 100-200mg potassium per serving. Gummies that meet these thresholds can meaningfully improve hydration status during exercise, travel, and illness. However, gummies with token electrolyte doses under 50mg sodium are unlikely to provide measurable hydration benefits beyond plain water.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When should I take electrolyte gummies?</summary>
      <p>Take electrolyte gummies 15-30 minutes before exercise to pre-load sodium and potassium, during prolonged activity lasting over 60 minutes, or immediately after exercise to replace sweat losses. For non-exercise use, take them during travel (especially flights), when recovering from illness, during hot weather, or first thing in the morning on a ketogenic diet. Consistent timing matters less than ensuring adequate total daily electrolyte intake.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How many electrolyte gummies should I take per day?</summary>
      <p>Follow the serving size on the product label, typically 2-4 gummies per serving. Most people need 1-2 servings daily under normal conditions. During heavy exercise, hot weather, or illness, you may need 2-3 servings spread throughout the day. Athletes who are heavy sweaters or train for more than 90 minutes may require additional servings. Monitor for signs of adequate hydration: pale yellow urine, no headaches, and no muscle cramps.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are electrolyte gummies better than electrolyte powder or drinks?</summary>
      <p>Electrolyte powders and drinks generally deliver higher electrolyte doses per serving and simultaneously provide the water needed for absorption. Gummies offer superior portability and convenience — no water bottle, no mixing, no spills. The trade-off is that gummies require you to drink water separately. For intense athletics where maximum electrolyte delivery matters, powders win. For daily hydration support, travel, and convenience, gummies are equally effective when paired with adequate water intake.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can you take too many electrolyte gummies?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Excessive sodium intake can raise blood pressure and cause water retention. Excessive potassium can cause hyperkalemia, which affects heart rhythm — though this is rare from food-based supplements at normal doses. Excessive magnesium from supplements can cause diarrhea and GI distress. Stick to the recommended serving size unless advised otherwise by a healthcare provider. People with kidney disease, heart conditions, or those taking blood pressure medications should consult a physician before using electrolyte supplements.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do electrolyte gummies contain sugar?</summary>
      <p>Most electrolyte gummies contain some sugar (2-5g per serving) because sugar aids in sodium absorption through the SGLT1 co-transport mechanism in the small intestine. This is the same principle behind oral rehydration solutions used in hospitals. Sugar-free options like <a href="#lmnt">LMNT</a> and <a href="#hi-lyte">Hi-Lyte</a> exist but may absorb slightly less efficiently. If you are monitoring sugar intake, look for options sweetened with stevia or monk fruit that keep sugar under 2g per serving.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are electrolyte gummies good for keto?</summary>
      <p>Electrolyte gummies are particularly beneficial on a ketogenic diet. Ketosis increases sodium, potassium, and magnesium excretion through the kidneys, leading to the "keto flu" — headaches, fatigue, muscle cramps, and brain fog. Supplementing 1,000-2,000mg sodium, 1,000mg potassium, and 300-400mg magnesium daily is widely recommended during keto adaptation. Choose sugar-free or low-sugar electrolyte gummies (under 2g per serving) such as <a href="#lmnt">LMNT</a> or <a href="#hi-lyte">Hi-Lyte</a> to avoid disrupting ketosis.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between electrolyte gummies and sports drinks?</summary>
      <p>Sports drinks combine electrolytes, water, and carbohydrates in a single liquid. Electrolyte gummies provide concentrated electrolytes in a portable solid form but require separate water intake. Sports drinks are ideal during exercise when you need simultaneous hydration and fuel. Electrolyte gummies are better for daily supplementation, travel, and situations where carrying liquids is impractical. Many athletes use both: gummies for convenience throughout the day, and sports drinks during training and competition.</p>
    </details>

